metadata.name: fx(haish) / the Generator #102
metadata.description:
fx(haish) is my contribution to #fxhashturnsone
fx(haish) is not a finished product
fx(haish) is a co-creation experiment
fx(haish) is a fun exploration of a mixed GenAI process

fx(haish) is my Happy Birthday to fx(hash). 

Have fun, collectors!


// HOW TO PARTICIPATE

Step 1. Mint or collect “fx(haish) - the Generator”
Step 2. Visit https://www.arqtistic.com/fx(haish) to generate your “fx(haish) - The AI City” based on your mint. You have 20 tries.
Step 3. Await further instructions.


// FURTHER INFO

This algorithm has been designed to produce images which are suitable for the subsequent AI generation. The token consists of a random number of randomly placed and sized rectangles, filled with a noise gradient pattern. In short, Diffusion AI Models thrive on noise.

The AI generation uses Stable Diffusion 1.5 through an API designed by the 330ai team (@Pixelmindai). The WebUI has been developed by Nik0gda (@AntonCebanu2). AI Prompt has been designed (by me) to produce images of Cities, but you can possibly make it do other things, if you try hard enough.

metadata.name: Alt Horizons #9
metadata.description:
"Beyond the horizon of the place we lived when we were young
In a world of magnets and miracles
Our thoughts strayed constantly and without boundary" 

*Pink Floyd - High Hopes*

Endless metaphoric horizons generated in p5js with 2 Cellular Automata rules. Sky may be heavy, sea may be rough or tranquil. These glitchy landscapes are programmed with the aim of a powerful Notan, but each generation is a game of chance.

Nōtan (濃淡) is a Japanese design concept involving the play and placement of light and dark elements. The underlying abstract framework upon which the structure of a painting is created.

Press "s" to save a high resolution PNG file for print (7x current resolution)

metadata.name: Snake Alley #315
metadata.description:
Snake Alley is a place in my neighborhood where the sidewalk is narrowly bounded by low-hanging branches on one side and a steep ditch one the other. I have seen countless snakes dart across the sidewalk there at dusk. 

I always wind up at Snake Alley, wearing sandals, at dusk.

This generative system creates unique outputs for each hash. The compositions are organized like spokes through a series of concentric rings, like the Dharmachakra, however these are twisted and centered around an out-spiraling function. Higher-torque versions look more twisted and gnarled, while low-torque versions look like rays emanating from the center.

A number of branches connect each outer ring with its adjacent, inner ring. The layers of branches fill the space with low, medium, or high density - full of circles drawn from the outer layers to the innermost layer. The circles themselves are small or large, within each output.

Fifteen color palettes named after different kinds of snakes were used to lightly color the edges, each drawn with equal likelihood. The titles and colors were adapted from different snake species, typically variants found in the southeastern US, when different colorations occur in other regions. The coral, corn, and milk snakes around Charleston have similar coloration in nature, and their similar color gradients reflect this fact.

I originally composed this artwork in the R Statistics language. I translated the system to p5.js for the one-year anniversary of fxhash. Proceeds from sales will go to Processing.org, the organization that is developing p5.js. #fxhashturnsone 

Verified NFT collectors can purchase a fine art print for their unique token at vadenart.com

About the artist: Kenny Vaden is a generative artist based in Charleston, SC. His art experience included drawing, painting, stained glass apprenticeships, and nature photography. Vaden’s code-based artworks are available online as limited edition or single edition fine art prints, as well as NFTs on Quantum.art, Flamingo DAO Flutter, OpenSea, Objkt, fxhash, and Foundation. More information about the artist and artwork is available on vadenart.com

metadata.name: Nebula, Solitude #25
metadata.description:
Nebula is one of the most magnificent stellar phenomena to behold. It is a distinct luminescent part of the interstellar medium, which consists of ionized gas and cosmic dust. Nebulae are often star-forming regions, where stars are born in solitude but surrounded by beautiful light and matter.

In this series, I continue the exploration of color and gravity, the effect of mass on speed, the effect of speed on hue, and how light can change by passing through big particles and dust systems.

I also want to let you participate in the creation of your artwork variation too. Each iteration is a unique and unpredictable dance of light in the dust and gravitation between matter clusters, however,  with the controls listed below, you can change the probability of light/dust blocks as well as the tiling layout.

[L] - create a new layout
[S] - reshuffle the current layout

[Shift] + [1] - change dust blocks probability to 0.0 and reshuffle the current layout
[Shift] + [2] - —//— 0.2
[Shift] + [3] - —//— 0.4
[Shift] + [4] - —//— 0.6
[Shift] + [5] - —//— 0.8
[Shift] + [6] - —//— 1.0

Basics:
[A] - skip/restart the animation

[1] - save PNG in low resolution
[2] - save PNG in medium resolution
[3] - save PNG in high resolution
[4] - save PNG in ultra-high resolution

Experimental zone:
[E] - toggle endless animation
[0] - save the current frame in low resolution

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.

Use Chrome 107 for the best experience, other browsers are significantly slower on this artwork, visual results also may vary.

Made with love and p5js

By Collapsar Beauty
CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.description:
The human spirit is an enigmatic one-of-a-kind. It has always been a conundrum for people who want to understand the depth of it, but no one has ever made it through. metadata.name: You Name It #9
metadata.description:
There are many questions and theories surrounding the magical mechanism of visual perception and how it is linked to our brain processing. 

How much knowledge we learn through perception is based on prior knowledge? 
How much of our perception do we receive directly, and how much do we infer? 

The brain combines external signals when a person explores their environment, leading to the perception of a persistent object. Even though an object is out of sight, it can still be remembered in mind via creative processes. 

When stimuli are spatially and temporally adjacent to one another, they may aggregate perceptually into prominent, coherent patterns or wholes. Our perceptual world is full of what we call a "gestalt, such as when leaves and branches group together to form trees and when trees combine to form forests; when eyes, ears, noses, and mouths arrange themselves into faces; when musical notes combine to form chords and melodies; and when countless dots or pixels come together to form a photograph. Our project is, in a sense challenge of perception, so what do you see? What comes into your mind as a perception when you look at it ??

Wait a moment it takes a while to be rendered
---
Created using vanilla javascript
KrouniHatim - Nov22

metadata.name: Let's Celebrate #13
metadata.description:
All peoples have established anniversaries to celebrate their victories, disorders, or misfortunes.
Having said that, people are social beings, and you cannot celebrate whatever it may be alone. So join those who are celebrating 
their success because they will join you in celebrating yours when the time comes. Then, as you praise and celebrate your life, 
there will be more life to enjoy. For all of the humans out there, remember that celebrations don't have to revolve around grandiose 
things. It's okay to celebrate a simple life. However, for all of us pursuing our passions, remember that although celebrating 
achievement is significant, learning from failure is much more crucial. while you cherish the milestones as you prepare for the road 
ahead.

Fxhash turns one, Happy birthday !

---

metadata.name: Frames #11
metadata.description:
Everyone has a different life narrative to share, and one particular incident can make all the difference in the world in how your life differs from everyone else's. We undoubtedly experience an unfathomable number of events during our lives, and the culmination of these situations has shaped who we are today. Yet, we only remember some of them. Each situation is entangled in the memory of our senses related to the events that occurred in that situation. Separately, events that we recall make the whole picture of our life inside a frame full of successions and intersections of scenes pictured within a limitless number of frames, each one presenting an event that we live. That's what makes our life a puzzle; you can only see the picture when you put all the pieces together.
